+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UfCDTEoHYK7ox7zqvkDvz7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XNDXD7AGypn6ywgVXySuXT","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"OUTPUT=$(gemini -p 'Implement the file src/index.ts for a TypeScript project.\n\nRead tsconfig.json and .eslintrc.cjs first to understand the project conventions.\n\nRequirements:\n1. Define and export an interface Machine with fields: target: boolean[] and buttons: number[][]\n2. Export a function solveToggle(machine: Machine): number[] | null\n3. Export a function solveCounter(lights: number[], buttons: number[][], modulus: number): number[] | null\n\nAlgorithm for solveToggle:\n4. Model as a system of linear equations over GF(2). Each light i gives equation: sum of b_j for buttons j that affect light i ≡ target[i] (mod 2). b_j in {0,1}.\n5. Build augmented matrix (numLights rows × (numButtons+1) cols) over GF(2). Entry [i][j] = 1 if button j toggles light i. Last column = target[i] ? 1 : 0.\n6. Perform Gaussian elimination over GF(2) with partial pivoting (prefer leftmost pivot column, then topmost row).\n7. After elimination, check for inconsistent rows (all zeros in coefficients but 1 in augmented column) — return null.\n8. Identify pivot columns and free variable columns. For each free variable assignment (enumerate all 2^k combinations where k = number of free vars), back-substitute to get all variable values, collecting valid solutions.\n9. Among all valid solutions, pick the one with minimum number of 1s (fewest button presses). Break ties by lexicographic order of the sorted button index array.\n10. Return sorted array of button indices where b_j=1, or null if no solution.\n\nAlgorithm for solveCounter:\n11. Model as system of linear equations over GF(p) where p = modulus (prime). Each counter i gives equation: sum of x_j for buttons j that affect counter i ≡ lights[i] (mod p). x_j in {0, 1, ..., p-1}.\n12. Build augmented matrix (numCounters rows × (numButtons+1) cols) over GF(p). Entry [i][j] = 1 if button j increments counter i. Last column = lights[i].\n13. Perform Gaussian elimination over GF(p) — use modular inverse for scaling.\n14. After elimination, check for inconsistent rows — return null.\n15. Identify pivot and free variable columns. Enumerate all p^k combinations of free variables (k = number of free vars).\n16. For each assignment, back-substitute to get all variable values (mod p).\n17. Among valid solutions, pick the one with minimum total presses (sum of all x_j). Break ties lexicographically.\n18. Return the result array where result[i] = number of presses for button i, or null.\n\nConstraints:\n- Language: TypeScript strict mode, ES2022, Node16 module system\n- No external dependencies — stdlib only\n- All arithmetic mod 2 (toggle) or mod p (counter) must be correct — never produce negative values\n- Must handle up to 40 buttons and 40 lights/counters efficiently. The free variable enumeration with 2^k or p^k could be large — if k is too large (e.g., more than 20 for toggle or total combos > 10M for counter), still need to handle it. For the counter case with large k, consider a smarter approach: when k>0, for each free variable enumerate 0..p-1 and use a greedy/DP approach to minimize total. Actually for both cases, if the number of free variables makes enumeration infeasible, use a branch-and-bound or just set free variables to minimize — for toggle, free vars to 0 minimizes count; for counter, free vars to 0 minimizes sum (then check if that gives lex smallest).\n- IMPORTANT OPTIMIZATION: If 2^k > some threshold (say 2^20) for toggle, or p^k > 10_000_000 for counter, do NOT enumerate all combinations. Instead, for toggle, setting all free variables to 0 gives a valid solution with fewest extra presses from free vars. For counter, setting all free vars to 0 also minimizes sum contribution from free vars. This greedy approach is correct for minimizing total presses when the system is underdetermined.\n- Actually wait — free variables DO affect pivot variables through back-substitution. So changing free vars can increase or decrease pivot var values. The greedy shortcut of setting free vars to 0 is NOT guaranteed optimal. For infeasible enumeration sizes, we need a smarter approach. For toggle (GF(2)), with k free vars, each pivot variable is a fixed XOR of some free vars. The total number of 1s = (number of 1s among pivot vars) + (number of 1s among free vars). Each pivot var equals some constant XOR some subset of free vars. This is equivalent to a minimum weight codeword problem which is NP-hard in general. For practical purposes with k<=40, if k>20 we may need heuristics, but the problem says up to 40 buttons total so k should be small in practice. Just enumerate when feasible, otherwise try all-zeros for free vars as best effort.\n- The function signatures and types must exactly match what I specified.\n- Use export for all public types and functions.\n\nOutput ONLY the TypeScript code. No markdown fences. No explanation.' -o text 2>&1)\necho \"$OUTPUT\"","description":"Delegate implementation to Gemini CLI","timeout":120000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":573,"cache_read_input_tokens":21912,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":573},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"48007c51-2b28-4eef-a12a-a868e5449043","uuid":"f3944324-486e-4188-b0d4-e32725311974"}
